comment:
“And… *fire!*”

The acrid scent of powder filled the air, followed by the sound of splintering wood and screams from the deck of the *Scourge*’s prey, a merchant ship riding low in the water.

‘Jolly Roger’, for once not *jolly* at all, stalked up and down the deck barking orders at all and sundry, sending sailors and officers alike scurrying to obey.  The battle was tipped heavily in their favour, but it had not been won just yet.

“Put yer backs into it, ye load o’ lubbers!”

The captain waved his cutlass in a very expressive—but not very safe—gesture in the direction of the other ship. “Bring ‘er in!” he shouted to the helmsman. “Some of ye best get ready to go over there so’s we can secure the prize and get ‘er back to port.”

From the look of things, not all of the merchantman’s crew had been cowed by the assault.  Whoever went over there would have quite a fight on their hands!

---

>**_Tutorial:_** 
>&nbsp; 
>_The narrative in a Storium game is driven by challenges like these ones.  The narrator sets the challenges and gives prompts for the outcomes, but it's up to the players to overcome the challenges and describe how the scene turns out._
>&nbsp; 
>_To do that, you'll need to use the cards in your hand to show how your character responds to and helps to resolve the issue.  A Strength card builds towards a Strong outcome, and represents the character positively influencing the situation.  A Weak card builds towards a Weak outcome, and represents the character negatively influencing the situation._
>&nbsp; 
>_Neutral cards, like your Subplot, have no inherent weight.  If a challenge is "trending Strong", then your neutral play will push the narrative closer to a Strong outcome (and thus should represent a positive effect on the situation).  If it is "trending Weak", then the **same play** will push the narrative closer to a Weak outcome and thus have a negative effect on the situation.  If it is the first card on a challenge, or if the challenge was previously "trending Uncertain", then the effect of your actions will be less clear, and you should leave it open for others to write._
>&nbsp; 
>_As all of these challenges are one point, you will all get to practice writing an outcome (or, if you play a Subplot, leaving space for me to write the outcome).  When you win control, you get to say how the challenge turns out, using the Narrator's prompt.  When the challenge ends Uncertain, stop before either outcome would be reached, to allow the Narrator to take over and tell you how it went._
>&nbsp;  
>_On justifying your card plays: You do not have to use the exact words that appear on the card. Showing your character making a clever deduction is better than writing: “Character was intelligent, so…”_
>&nbsp; 
>_One thing I really try to stress is that Weak outcomes are not Bad, necessarily.  Mostly I try to keep Weak outcomes to either "success but" (where there is a cost or a complication or the success is delayed) or a failure that enables the *player* to do something clever or fun._
>&nbsp;  
>_Another thing to bear in mind with regards to Strong and Weak outcomes: it may seem "better" to get Strong outcomes—but sooner or later you will run out of Strengths.  You must use **all** of the Strengths **and** Weaknesses in your hand before you get to "refresh your hand" and pick new ones.  That's a reason to play Weak cards over and above it just being fun!_
